Wash and dry produce.

Dice @onion{1}(diced into 1/2-inch pieces). Pick @cilantro{1/4%ounce} leaves from stems. Reserve leaves; finely chop stems.

In a #large pot{}, heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} over medium-high heat. Add onion and cilantro stems; cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add @cumin{1%teaspoon}, @smoked paprika{1%teaspoon}, and half the @garlic powder{2%teaspoon} (you'll use the rest in the next step); continue to cook, stirring occasionally, until fragrant, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Stir in @mushroom stock concentrate{2}, @crushed tomatoes{1}, @chickpeas{1} and their liquid, @sugar{1%tsp}, and @salt{1%tsp}. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a simmer. Cover and cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly thickened, ~{15-20%minutes}.

While stew cooks, in a #small microwave-safe bowl{}, combine @harissa powder{1%tablespoon}, remaining garlic powder, @olive oil{3%tbsp}, @salt{1/2%tsp}, and @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} (add as many as you like). Cover with #plastic wrap{} and microwave until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir to combine. Set aside, covered, until ready to serve.

Wrap @pitas{2} in damp #paper towels{} and microwave until warm and pliable, ~{30-60%seconds}.

In a second #small bowl{}, combine @za'atar spice{1%tablespoon}, @sesame seeds{1%tablespoon}, @olive oil{3%tbsp}, and a pinch of @salt{} to taste.

Lightly brush pitas with as much za'atar oil as you like. Cut each pita into four triangles.

Once stew has slightly thickened, use a #potato masher{} or the back of a #large spoon{} to gently mash about half the chickpeas (this will help thicken the stew even more!). Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if desired.

Divide stew between bowls. Top with cilantro leaves, @yogurt{2%tablespoon}, and as much harissa oil as you like. Serve with za'atar-spiced pitas and any remaining za'atar oil on the side for dipping.